BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:INKspire Celebration and Book Launch
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260503T120000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260503T150000
UID:bm-4840620260503@shop.benmcnallybooks.com
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://cdn1.bookmanager.com/i/7600763/Website2/
 Events/2026_INKspire.png?cb=1773343138
DESCRIPTION:[at Ben McNally Books]\nJoin us at Ben McNally Books to celebr
 ate the end of the INKspire’s Writer Fellowship Program and the publicat
 ion of INKspire's inaugural print anthology!\nINKspire’s Writer Fellows 
 will be presenting their work during the first hour\, and there will be ti
 me for mingling and refreshments afterwards.\nRSVP HERE\nAbout INKspire\nI
 NKspire is a youth-led nonprofit organization that aims to amplify the voi
 ces of youth by providing a safe and inclusive platform. The Writer Fellow
 ship Program is a free\, year-long program designed to support and develop
  emerging women and nonbinary writers ages 18-24. This program offers a st
 ructured opportunity to gain hands-on publishing experience\, build a prof
 essional writing portfolio\, and engage with Toronto’s literary communit
 y through mentorship\, workshops\, and collaborative projects.
LOCATION:Ben McNally Books
URL:https://shop.benmcnallybooks.com/events
X-SOURCE:Ben McNally Books
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Author Talk: Keiko Honda
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260504T170000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260504T190000
UID:bm-4707920260504@shop.benmcnallybooks.com
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://cdn1.bookmanager.com/i/7600763/Website2/
 Events/2026_Keiko_Honda.png?cb=1771875722
DESCRIPTION:[at Ben McNally Books]\nJoin Ben McNally Books and Keiko Honda
  for a conversation about two recently published works that explore differ
 ent forms of discovery and witness:\nHidden Flowers\n(Heritage House\, 202
 5)\, named to\nCBC Books' 45 Must-Read Books of Fall 2025\n\, uncovers sto
 ries of strength and beauty in places most people never notice.\nThe Broke
 n Map Home\n(Caitlin Press\, 2025) presents Honda's translation of her lat
 e grandfather's extraordinary account of survival\, repatriation\, and the
  long journey home from Korea after Japan's surrender in 1945.\nBoth books
  required Honda to become a translator—not just between Japanese and Eng
 lish\, but between silence and speech\, between what was hidden and what n
 eeded to be seen.\nHidden Flowers\nasked her to make the invisible visible
 .\nThe Broken Map Home\nasked her to carry her grandfather's voice across 
 seventy years and two languages while honoring what remained unspoken.\nHo
 nda will discuss her writing journey for both books: the craft decisions\,
  the ethical questions\, the challenge of bearing witness to difficult his
 tories while finding beauty without erasing complexity. She'll share what 
 she learned about translation in its deepest sense—as an act of attentio
 n\, discovery\, and care.\nAbout the Author\nKeiko Honda is a scientist\, 
 writer\, community organizer\, and painter. She holds a PhD in internation
 al community health from New York University and had a research career at 
 Columbia University\, which was interrupted when she suddenly contracted a
  rare autoimmune disease that confined her to a wheelchair for life. After
  moving to Vancouver in 2009\, Honda began hosting artist salons\, for whi
 ch she was awarded the City of Vancouver’s Remarkable Women Award in 201
 4. Shortly thereafter\, she founded the Vancouver Arts Colloquium Society 
 to bridge generations and cultures through the arts and to offer members o
 f marginalized communities opportunities for artistic self-discovery. She 
 teaches the aesthetics of co-creation in the Liberal Arts and 55+ Program 
 at Simon Fraser University.
LOCATION:Ben McNally Books
URL:https://shop.benmcnallybooks.com/events
X-SOURCE:Ben McNally Books
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Doubles Book Launch
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260505T170000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260505T190000
UID:bm-4708220260505@shop.benmcnallybooks.com
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://cdn1.bookmanager.com/i/7600763/Website2/
 Events/2026_Nora_Gold.png?cb=1771877680
DESCRIPTION:[at Ben McNally Books]\nJoin us at Ben McNally Books\, in part
 nership with Geurnica Editions\, to celebrate the launch of\nDoubles\n\,
  by Nora Gold.\nOrder a Copy of the book here.\nAbout the Book\nDoubles\n
 takes place in 1968 in an institution for troubled youth\, and is told fro
 m the perspective of a brilliant\, spunky\, 12-year-old girl who is obsess
 ed with math.\nEngagingly written and often funny\, this novella explores 
 how a sensitive young teenager changes over a six-month period from a poli
 te\, quiet “good girl” into a delinquent.\nAlthough set in the past\,\
 nDoubles\nhas direct relevance to today\, with our recently heightened awa
 reness of the harsh reality in some of our residential institutions during
  that era (including for Indigenous children\, but not only).\nAbout the A
 uthor\nDr. Nora Gold is the prize-winning author of five books and the rec
 ipient of multiple awards\, including a Canadian Jewish Literary Award\, a
  Vine Canadian Jewish Book Award\, and a Canada Council translation grant.
  Her writing has been praised by Cynthia Ozick\, Alice Munro\, and Publish
 ers Weekly\, and has received international acclaim\, including from the N
 ew York Times Wirecutter\, Los Angeles Review of Books\, and Hadassah Maga
 zine.\nA former professor\, Gold is also the founder and editor of the pre
 stigious literary journal Jewish Fiction (www.jewishfiction.com)\, which h
 as published 650 stories originally written in 23 languages. She’s appea
 red on podcasts in Canada\, USA\, Spain\, India\, and Australia\, and has 
 over 100\,000 followers on LinkedIn. noragold.com
LOCATION:Ben McNally Books
URL:https://shop.benmcnallybooks.com/events
X-SOURCE:Ben McNally Books
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:From Ragged Ass Road to Rideau Hall Book Launch
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260507T170000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260507T190000
UID:bm-4708320260507@shop.benmcnallybooks.com
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://cdn1.bookmanager.com/i/7600763/Website2/
 Events/2026_Whit_Fraser.png?cb=1771878126
DESCRIPTION:[at Ben McNally Books]\nJoin us at Ben McNally Books\, in part
 nership with Douglas McIntyre\, to celebrate the launch of\nFrom Ragged As
 s Road to Rideau Hall\n\, by Whit Fraser.\nOrder a Copy of the book here.
 \nAbout the Book\nVeteran journalist Whit Fraser recounts the stories behi
 nd the stories in this collection of tales drawn from fifty years of repor
 ting on nation-changing events.\nFrom Ragged Ass Road to Rideau Hall\nis a
  sweeping memoir from veteran journalist and northern chronicler Whit Fras
 er\, tracing a lifetime spent at the front lines of the events that shaped
  modern Canada. From his youth in Nova Scotia to decades reporting across 
 the Arctic\, Fraser offers a riveting\, behind-the-scenes account of major
  national turning points—stories he reported on up close\, but never ful
 ly had the chance to tell until now.\nFraser brings readers into the cold\
 , stunned morning when the Soviet satellite Cosmos 954 rained nuclear debr
 is across the Northwest Territories\, igniting one of the most secretive i
 nternational military operations in Canadian history. He revisits the trag
 edy of the Ocean Ranger\, one of the world’s most advanced oil rigs that
  became the site of an unthinkable disaster. On Parliament Hill\, he repor
 ts from inside the storm of the National Energy Program and the tense cons
 titutional negotiations that affirmed Indigenous rights while dividing the
  nation anew.\nWoven throughout is Fraser’s personal journey—his years
  living in the North\, his friendships with leaders who transformed the po
 litical landscape\, and his partnership with Mary Simon\, whose swearing-i
 n as Canada’s first Indigenous Governor General brings his story full ci
 rcle.\nAnchored by vivid reporting and personal reflection\,\nFrom Ragged 
 Ass Road to Rideau Hall\nis a powerful journey through the people\, politi
 cs\, and places that have defined Canada—and the shifting landscape of j
 ournalism itself.\nAbout the Author\nWhit Fraser is a journalist\, broadca
 ster\, author\, and spouse of Canada’s Governor General\, Mary Simon. Ov
 er his long career with the CBC\, he has covered Arctic news\, worked for 
 eight years on Parliament Hill\, and worked as a primetime anchor for CBC 
 Newsworld. Fraser was the founding chair of the Canadian Polar Commission 
 (1991–97) and executive director of Inuit Tapiriit Kanatami (2001–06)\
 , an organization founded in 1971 to give national representation to Inuit
  voices. He is the author of True North Rising (Penguin\, 2019)\, a memoir
  which won the NorthWords Book Prize\, and Cold Edge of Heaven (Boulder Bo
 oks\, 2022). Fraser and Simon now live at Rideau Hall in Ottawa where they
  continue in public service
LOCATION:Ben McNally Books
URL:https://shop.benmcnallybooks.com/events
X-SOURCE:Ben McNally Books
END:VEVENT
